title: Was John the Baptist a Real Historical Figure Related to Jesus? Rabbi Tovia Singer Will Surprise You
description:
Was John the Baptist, also known as John the immerser, a real Jewish figure, an authoritative Jewish figure, and connected to Jesus? A caller asks Rabbi Tovia Singer.

Rabbi Tovia Singer explains John the Baptist was also known as John the Immerser, or Yochanan the Immerser. The Jewish historian Josephus mentioned about him in the Jewish Antiquities, therefore we can be sure that he was a noted figure. 

Later gospel writers would want to connect Jesus with John the Baptist even more than before. And that is when we find a massive splash of it in the gospel according to Luke. In the Book of Luke, John the Baptist is introduced as a family member of Jesus. There, they were cousins.

However, Rabbi Tovia Singer invites his audience to question, how likely this would be. He continues to point out that Mark and Matthew, the earlier gospels didn't think that this connection between John the Baptist and Jesus was significant enough to mention in their books. 

In the earlier text of the gospels, however, the notion that John the Baptist did not know who Jesus was, also crept in. In this video, Rabbi Tovia Singer continues to explain how very often historical facts are mixed into the narrative of the Christian gospels, next to events we strongly believe are fiction.

title: Rabbi Tovia Singer: Why did God speak in the Hebrew language?
description:
Rabbi Tovia Singer receives an interesting call, challenging him regarding the Hebrew language of the bible. 

When one reads the bible, they will see that the names are all in Hebrew, even God's name is in Hebrew. The caller asks why does it have to be that the original language of the bible is Hebrew, and thus seem to alleviate a particular culture above all other culture. 

The caller continues to point out that even before Abraham realized there was one God, even in the time of Noah, Noah is not a Jew and he had a Hebrew name. 

Is Hebrew the original language of the Bible? Did Adam speak Hebrew? Was Hebrew the first language on earth? Did God really speak in the Hebrew language?

title: Kosher Food and Kindness to Animals: What Does the Torah Teach? [2018]
description:
Kosher Food and Kindness to Animals: What Does the Torah Teach? 

Rabbi Tovia Singer explores the topic of kosher food and kindness to animals in general, according to Torah laws. He continues the session by shedding light on the corruption by the apostle Paul regarding a certain verse in the Jewish bible on treating animals.

The topic regarding bible corruption by Paul, the apostle, started with Rabbi Tovia Singer responding to a caller's question regarding kosher food and kindness to animals. 

The first discussion was based on the following question on kosher food: Does the food that an animal eats determine if it is kosher for Jews to eat? Rabbi Tovia Singer explains what the standard the Torah uses to determine an animal to be kosher or not. There are two signs of kosher animals: chewing of cuds, and split hooves. The fact that kosher animals chew their cuds only says that the animals are only eating plants. However, what the menu is on their diet in itself is not what should be used to decide if the animal is kosher. 

The discussion continues on what the Torah says regarding kindness to animals: What does  Deut 25:4 mean by forbidding to muzzle an "ox when it is treading the grain"? How does the Torah endorse kindness to animals? 

Rabbi Tovia Singer widens the discussion beyond the scope of the question of this session towards two direction. First, animals meant for slaughter will become sick if they suffer while they are alive. Thus, rendering the meat not kosher to eat for Jews. Second, Paul the apostle completely misquote this passage of Torah, regarding showing kindness to animals, in Corinthians 9:9 and twisted it to sound as if God is not at all concerned about showing mercy towards animals.

Watch the complete video explanation with Rabbi Tovia Singer.

Rabbi Tovia Singer answers this interesting question by explaining first that that the last book of the Jewish Bible is Malachi. In this book, it was prophesied that the prophet Elijah will be the one prophet that will usher in the Messianic age. 

This causes a complication in the Christian belief that Jesus is the Messiah. If he was really the Messiah, then where is Elijah that would be the one who is prophesied to usher this specific age? It is  in Christianity's great interest that Jesus should be connected to somebody in his time that would be actively reminding the people of the end of times. John the Baptist was the perfect candidate. 

This is the reason why the Gospel according to Matthew confirms that John the Baptist is Elijah. However, the Gospel according to John does not. Why is that? Rabbi Tovia Singer explores the answer in this video.

title: Masada: Rabbi Tovia Singer Questions Act of Jewish Mass Suicide
description:

However, before Roman troops could enter the fortress, in a desperate act of mass suicide, nearly 1,000 Jews killed each other rather than become slaves to Rome.  In his moving tour atop of Masada, Rabbi Tovia Singer explores the historical context of this horrific event, and questions the desperate act of zealous Sicarii on moral grounds. These passages clearly state that the sacrificial system, including the sin and Passover offering, will resume upon the rebuilding of the Temple.  If, as Paul claims, Jesus was the final sacrifice “once and for all” (Romans 6:10), and the animal sacrificial system was merely a temporary “foreshadowing” of Calvary (Hebrews 10:18), why will animal sacrifices be restored during the messianic era? Moreover, why would Jesus have to bring a bull as a sin offering in the future Temple (Ezekiel 45:22) when Church teachings clearly state that Jesus was sinless, and was himself the sin sacrifice? title: Why doesn't Judaism accept the Christian Messiah?  Rabbi Tovia Singer Responds
description:
Christians are so convinced that Jesus is the messiah, they are utterly astounded that the Jews, of all people, consider this claim preposterous. Christians are bewildered by this rejection because it appears so obvious to them that every aspect of Jesus’ life—from his miraculous conception to his crucifixion and resurrection—was clearly predicted in the Jewish Scriptures. They wonder why the Jews then fail to embrace Jesus as their messiah. Can’t they grasp that the prophecies in their own Bible predict that the messiah would suffer and die and then rise from the grave? How can a people who produced so many Nobel Prize winners be so dense? Are they just plain stubborn?

Why then did the Jews reject the claim that the messiah would suffer and die for the sins of the world? The answer is quite simple: Jewish messianic expectations are firmly rooted in hundreds of prophecies recorded throughout the Hebrew Bible. In this fascinating broadcast, Rabbi Tovia Singer explains why Jews who are anticipating the coming of the messiah are not looking for anyone remotely like Jesus.

title: Rabbi Tovia Singer Slams Bogus Claim that NT Quoted Septuagint Because it is Superior to the Hebrew
description:
Christian apologists frequently defend Matthew’s translation of the Hebrew word alma as “virgin” by citing the Septuagint version of Isaiah. They argue that the Septuagint, a Greek translation of the Hebrew Scriptures rendered by Jewish scholars approximately 2,200 years ago, employed the Greek word for “virgin,” (“parthenos”) in Isaiah 7:14. They conclude, therefore, that the original text must have been understood to mean “virgin,” and Matthew, who was writing in Greek about the virgin birth of Jesus, was quoting the passage from the Septuagint rather than the Hebrew text.  Moreover, missionaries argue that the Septuagint, which was translated more than 2,000 years ago, is far more reliable than the Masoretic Text (MT), which was compiled 1,200 years ago.  Is this a valid claim?

This is one of those explanations that sound plausible until you dig a bit and think a bit more.  In this powerful presentation, Rabbi Tovia Singer demonstrates that this well-worn argument is completely erroneous and deeply misleading.

title: Why are Flood Stories so Prevalent in the Ancient World? Did it Happen? Rabbi Tovia Singer Responds
description:
While the Biblical account of Noah’s flood is the most well-known flood tradition, there are numerous other narratives that are thousands of years old, and many of them predate the Torah.  These various myths are prevalent across time and found in almost every civilization.  Although all the flood stories vary, sometimes to large degrees, many of them have striking threads of commonality. Often these stories are told about one human family that survives on a ship. Animals are involved in many of these stories and there is almost always a moral, with the flood coming only after the human race has committed some wrong doing.  In this fascinating broadcast, Rabbi Tovia Singer explains why we encounter this account in almost every culture of human civilization.

title: Woe to You, Hypocrites! Murders of the Prophets! Rabbi Tovia Singer Responds to NT Charges
description:
Many historians trace 2,000 years of anti-Jewish persecution directly back to certain pronouncements placed in the mouth of Jesus by the authors of the New Testament.  Although the Church widely considers the Gospel of Matthew to be the “most Jewish” of the Gospels, it contains some of the most anti-Jewish passages found in the New Testament.  As Matthew’s narrative marches toward the Passion, the anti-Jewish rhetoric increases. We are told in chapter 23 that Jesus launched a series of virulently hostile accusations against the Jews, which include the collective charge of despicable hypocrisy, as well as direct culpability for the murder of the Prophets and all the innocent victims found in Scripture.  These serious indictments were not just charged against those in his audience.  Rather, they were launched against all Jews collectively, of all generations.

Consequently, these and other passages in the New Testament stereotyped the Jewish people for all time as an icon of unredeemed humanity: the image of a blind, stubborn, carnal and perverse nation. This dehumanization, no doubt, is the vehicle that formed the psychological prerequisite to the Church’s unrelenting atrocities against Jewish communities centuries later.

In this eye-opening broadcast Rabbi Tovia Singer examines the most serious charges found in Matthew 23 in light of the evangelist’s troubling Passion Narrative.

title: Was Paul Really a Student of Rabbi Gamaliel, Doctor of Jewish Law? Rabbi Singer Responds
description:

Rabbi Gamaliel also known as Gamaliel the Elder, was a leading authority in the Sanhedrin during the first century CE. He was the grandson of the great Jewish teacher Rabbi Hillel the Elder, through his son, Simeon ben Hillel. In the Talmud, Gamaliel is recorded as a Nasi or prince and a Rabban or our master. He once held the position of the President of the Great Sanhedrin in Jerusalem. He was extremely revered as the greatest teachers being spoken about in the Mishnah, "Since Rabban Gamaliel the Elder died, there is been no more reverence for the law, and purity and piety died out at the same time." (Sotah 9:15) 

Rabbi Tovia Singer explains how it would have been inconceivable for a man claimed as coming from Tarsus, to be a student of such a great a holy man in Jewish history.

Against all odds, a small band of faithful Jews, under the leadership of Mattityahu, defeated one of the world’s most powerful armies.  They reclaimed the holy Temple in Jerusalem and rededicated it to God.  The details of this startling victory are outlined in the Book of Maccabees.   Moreover, we are told by our sages that when the Jews sought to light the Temple's menorah, they discovered only a single cruse of pure olive oil.  Miraculously, the one-day supply burned for eight days.  In this fascinating broadcast, Rabbi Tovia Singer explains why the Jewish people emphasize the miracle of lights and relegate the Book of Maccabees to the Apocrypha. description:
Some Christians believe that Jesus and God is the same, and therefore there is no second person introduced to God; that God is one in this concept. At the same time they also believe in the Christian trinity.

Rabbi Tovia Singer receives a question regarding the argument that Jesus and God is the same person. According to this concept, God is one, who is also Jesus, and therefore, there is no second god. No violation to the Torah concept that God is one exists in this concept.  

Rabbi Tovia Singer explains that there was a time before the word "trinity" was invented. The word "Christian trinity" is not written in the bible and was only invented by Tertullian, born in the year 165. He converted into Christianity in 197. 

In those days, there was on of many concepts to understand who and what Jesus, named "modalism". At the time, modalism was considered a heresy.

By the second century, many Christians believed that Jesus and God was the same, meaning that he was both human and fully divine.  This assertion, however, sparked bitter arguments and a theological conundrum in the early church.   Christian leaders struggled with a fundamental problem: How would they reject the pagan notion that there are many gods, yet retain the firm monotheism expressed in the Jewish Scriptures?  

Rabbi Tovia Singer explains that one popular solution was to say that Jesus was actually God the Father himself, who became a human. This idea, often labeled modalism since it argues that the one God has different modes of existence, was attacked because it spawned staggering problems for Christian thinkers.

title: Is Jesus the Passover Lamb? [Rabbi Tovia Singer]
description:
Christians claim that Jesus is the passover lamb, referring to the lamb slaughtered in the land of Egypt. Is this true? 

Rabbi Tovia Singer is the Director of Outreach Judaism, who has been helping Jews return to the Jewish faith. He starts his explanation by pointing out why the Jews brought the Passover Lamb while still in the land of Egypt. 

The Egyptian thought of the lamb as a deity. It was forbidden to slaughter lambs throughout the land of Egypt. This was mentioned by Moses when Pharaoh told him to bring his sacrifice within the land. He told the Pharaoh that if they did that, the Egyptians will stone the Israelites for sacrificing their god.

The command to bring the passover lamb while they were still in Egypt is a test by God to see if the Israelites were worthy to be redeemed out of slavery in Egypt. Not only were they told to slaughter the god of Egypt, they are to smear its blood on the outside of their door as well. It was a test. If they complied, they will live. If not, they will die, when the angel of death and darkness walk the land of Egypt to kill every firstborn.

Understanding this important message is very important to answer the question, whether Jesus could have been the "passover lamb".  Rabbi Tovia Singer connects the dots in this video. 

Once the biblical context behind of the story is understood, it becomes apparent how absurd it is to suggest that the story has anything to do with Jesus. Even within christianity, it is a matter of wide dispute whether or not Jesus is considered the sacrificial lamb by the new testament. Either the last supper was a passover seder, or Jesus was the sacrificial lamb - according to the new testament, only one can be true.
